		<header>
			
			<h1>Commissioner Borg addresses the European Parliament on FPAs</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 September 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The EU Fisheries Commissioner, Joe Borg, detailed his vision on fisheries partnership agreements in a speech to the fisheries committee of the European Parliament on September 14th 2005. Stating that what the EU wants is ‘a long-distance fleet that is capable of supplying the European market, whilst fully respecting the appropriate norms and conditions’. He announced a wide consultation on the implementation of this policy, which should involve the Parliament, the Council, the sector itself and civil society.</p><p> He highlighted that ‘On many occasions the European Parliament has stressed the need to cover all fisheries agreements in one single political framework’. In response to this ‘Since 1 May 2005 all bilateral fisheries agreements are dealt with by the directorate in charge of external policy and markets within DG Fisheries and Maritime Affairs’.</p><p> He also emphasised that ‘Our partnership in fisheries should cover the entire value chain from the catch to the market. It must encompass scientific cooperation, conservation, monitoring and control, investment and processing and in so doing, yield positive labour-market effects’. He accepted that ‘the Commission has been criticised for a lack of transparency in its fisheries agreements, in particular when it comes to the manner in which the financial contributions of the agreements are disbursed and utilised by recipient governments’. On the financial aspects, ‘most of the agreements concluded by the Community were overestimated’, and therefore, ‘as requested by the Parliament, we have started a thorough revision of the agreements and, consequently, envisage a strong reduction of the compensation paid from the Community budget’.</p><p> Commissioner Borg recognised ‘the constraints that we face in the conclusion of fisheries partnership agreements. In some cases this relates to over-fishing, within a particular area and with respect to certain stocks. Furthermore, we sometimes have to cope with the inadequate control and surveillance capabilities of our partner countries in order to fight IUU fishing. We also face lacunae in the scientific advice and knowledge of partner countries with respect to some of the stocks’.</p><p> In the latter regard, the Commission has announced that, at the end of November 2005, it will organise an international seminar in Mauritius with a view to establishing an action plan for improving the quality and the availability of scientific advice. Finally, Commissioner Borg expressed the wish of the EU to ‘consolidate the network of fisheries partnership agreements, in particular the tuna agreements in the Pacific, the Indian Ocean and the Gulf of Guinea and the mixed-species agreements in western Africa’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Commissioner Borg’s speech, September 14th 2005: ‘The common fisheries policy’s external dimension: where do we stand and where do we want to go?’ </p><p>

<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/fisheries/news_corner/discours/speech80_en.htm" target="_self">http://europa.eu.int/comm/fisheries/news_corner/discours/speech80_en.htm</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> This speech highlights some crucial issues for future ACP-EU fisheries relations, and shows some positive signs. The announcement that a wide consultation on the implementation of FPAs is planned is definitely most welcome.</p><p> This consultation could also provide an opportunity to improve the implementation of the Council’s conclusions on FPAs, in terms of ‘enhanced policy dialogue with partner countries and stakeholders’. One must recognise that progress have been made in this regard through the set up of joint commissions in the framework of the FPAs. However, it is important that the ACP-EU political dialogue on the various challenges of a partnership could also take place outside the limited context of the bilateral negotiations.</p><p> The Commissioner’s declaration that ‘partnership in fisheries should cover the entire value chain from the catch to the market’ is a very important aspect for ACP countries if partnerships are to provide long-term benefits.</p><p> The issue of the lack of transparency in the use made by third countries of the financial compensation provided for in the agreement raises some fundamental questions. If the financial compensation is a payment made for fishing opportunities, then the third country is free to spend it as it wishes without formal need for reporting to the paying party. However, if the financial compensation is provided for development activities, then compensation levels should not depend on the level of fishing possibilities provided, but rather on the development needs identified. Resolving these questions is at the heart of the FPA debate with ACP countries.</p><p> In any case, if there is to be a ‘strong reduction of the compensation paid from the Community budget’, this will need to be compensated for by financial support from other sources (boat owners’ contributions, development cooperation, etc) so that sustainable fisheries development costs (research, monitoring, surveillance and control, etc) can be met.</p><p> Finally, the internal reorganisation of the services of the Commission, which is a decision at the executive level, even if it is most welcome, does not provide a full answer to the Parliament’s request that all fisheries agreements should be covered in one single political framework.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
